FINAL PROJECT
Prithvikiran Premkumar
CSCI 5229 - Final Project: "Groundskeeper"

================================================================================
  WHAT THE PROGRAM DOES
================================================================================

A 3D lawn-care simulator in which the user drives a riding mower around an
undulating parametric yard, cuts the grass (visible mowed stripes appear on
the terrain), and watches grass clippings spray from the mower deck via a true
GPU particle system.  The project was designed to incorporate as many OpenGL
and GLSL concepts from the course as possible into a single cohesive scene.

Features at a glance:
  - Drivable riding mower with steering, collision detection, and blade spin
  - Mowing mechanic: a grid tracks cut/uncut cells; terrain colour updates live
  - Parametric terrain with analytical normals (undulating sinusoidal surface)
  - Day/night cycle with smooth sunrise/sunset sky colour transitions
  - Mower headlight spotlight that activates automatically at night
  - GLSL per-pixel lighting shader on terrain (terrain.vert / terrain.frag)
  - Grass-clipping particle system (particle.vert / particle.frag) [GPU]
  - GPU rain particle system (rain.vert / rain.frag) -- auto in Wet mode
  - Waving flag: animated parametric surface with per-frame analytical normals
  - Sprinkler with Bezier water arc (glMap1d / glEvalMesh1)
  - Mouse object selection via colour picking; click -> Inspector
  - Object Inspector mode: turntable + orbiting light for every scene object
  - Surface normal indicators in Inspector
  - Three fog modes (EXP / EXP2 / LINEAR)[ controlling fog density ] with fog-matched sky colour
  - Five camera modes: ortho, perspective, first-person walk, follow, mower seat
  - Display list for fence geometry
  - Polygon offset for gravel path (no z-fighting with terrain)
  - Full help overlay (h key)

================================================================================
  HOW TO BUILD AND RUN
================================================================================

    make
    ./final

   | press 'h' for the help overlay . |

================================================================================
  WHAT TO LOOK AT FIRST  
================================================================================

 

  1. Press 4, then W/S to drive the mower.  Watch grass stripes appear.
     Particles spray from the deck in real time.

  2. Press g to toggle the GLSL per-pixel shader ON/OFF on the terrain. 
     The difference is immediately visible -- compare flat vs smooth lighting.

  3. Press r to cycle terrain modes (Dry -> Moderate -> Wet).
     In Wet mode, rain starts automatically (GPU particle system).
     Press y to toggle rain manually at any time.

  4. Press 2 for the best overhead view of the full yard.
     Press f to toggle fog, then ; to cycle EXP / EXP2 / LINEAR fog modes.[ FOG DENSITY DEMONSTRATION]

  5. Press i then n/N to cycle through all 10 objects in the Inspector.
     Press v inside the Inspector to see surface normal indicators.
     Click any object in the scene to jump directly to its Inspector entry.

  6. Press h at any time for the full key-bindings help overlay.

  7. Press space then , or . to sweep the sun manually through the day/night
     cycle and watch the sky colour, headlight, and fog colour all change.



================================================================================
  WHY THIS DESERVES AN A  --  TECHNICAL HIGHLIGHTS
================================================================================

--- 1. GLSL PER-PIXEL LIGHTING SHADER (flag.vert,flag.frag) ---

   
  The waving flag is actually the better showcase for per-pixel shading --
  the flag is a curved smoothly varying surface, so per-vertex lighting would
  interpolate colour across each quad from just the corner normals, missing
  the actual wave curvature between vertices.  Per-pixel shading uses the
  analytically computed normal at every fragment, so lighting accurately
  follows the wave shape everywhere.

Other implementation of this concept for terrain :

  The shader adds several features beyond basic per-pixel lighting:
    - terrainMode uniform: Dry (yellowish tint), Moderate (green), Wet (dark)
    - SunHeight uniform: diffuse intensity scales with sun elevation
    - Time-of-day tinting: warm orange at dawn/dusk blended in the fragment shader
    - Slope-based colour blend: steeper normals darken toward a soil colour
    - Distance darkening: fragments further from camera fade slightly
    - Mowed-cell colour: cut cells are passed as a vertex colour and blended
      in the fragment shader so the mowing stripes integrate with the lighting



--- 2. GPU RAIN PARTICLE SYSTEM (rain.vert / rain.frag) ---

  The rain system uses the GPU-driven philosophy for 15,000 raindrops.
  The CPU sets spawn XYZ and a phase offset once; the vertex shader computes
  each drop's current Y position using a repeating fall equation:

      current_y = FieldHeight - fmod((Time * FallSpeed + phase), FieldHeight)

  All 15,000 drops cycle through their fall simultaneously on the GPU.
  On the CPU, 15,000 position updates at 60 fps [ refresh rate ] would be 900,000 calculations
  per second.  On the GPU they happen in a single parallel pass.  The rain
  activates automatically when terrainMode is set to Wet (press r twice) or
  can be toggled manually with y. [ NOTE IT CAN HANDLE MORE PARTICLES BUT THIS NUMBER WAS IDEAL FOR THIS SCENERIO]

--- 3. WAVING FLAG -- ANIMATED PARAMETRIC SURFACE WITH ANALYTICAL NORMALS ---

  The flag is a parametric cloth surface whose vertex Z displacement follows:

      z = amplitude(x) * sin(freq*x - speed*t)

  where amplitude tapers to zero at the pole so the cloth looks pinned.
  Crucially, the surface normal is computed analytically each frame from the
  partial derivative dz/dx -- the same technique used for the static terrain,
  but applied to a moving surface.  This means normals are always mathematically
  correct as the flag waves, so per-pixel lighting on the flag cloth (via
  shader_flag) shades realistically at every pose.  Two-sided lighting is
  enabled so the back face of the flag shades differently from the front.

--- 4. COLLISION DETECTION WITH SLIDING RESPONSE ---

  The mower collides against two obstacle types:
    - Circular obstacles: trees, dustbins, crates, flagpole, sprinkler
    - Rotated-box obstacles: house (45 deg) and shed (-30 deg)

  Box collision transforms the mower into the obstacle's local frame for an
  AABB test, then rotates the outward normal back to world space.  The response
  is a SLIDE: only the penetrating component of the displacement vector is
  cancelled, so the mower glances off smoothly rather than stopping dead.

--- 6. MOUSE OBJECT SELECTION (COLOUR PICKING) ---

  Each pickable object is drawn in a hidden colour-ID pass with its Inspector
  index encoded in the alpha channel (glColor4ub(..., id)).  glReadPixels reads
  a (2R+1)x(2R+1) box around the cursor for robustness with thin objects like
  the fence rail and hedge.  Left-clicking a highlighted object jumps directly
  into Inspector mode on that object.  Per-object hitbox sizes and rotations
  match the real geometry so even rotated objects (house, shed) are reliably
  selectable.


================================================================================
  KEY ADDITIONS FROM HW3
================================================================================

  Beyond adding new objects (flag, sprinkler, rain) and fixing the fence
  floating bug (posts now placed at TerrainHeight()), the major additions are:

  1.  Mowing mechanic -- MOW_N x MOW_N grid tracks cut/uncut cells
  2.  GLSL per-pixel terrain shader with seasonal/weather modes
  3.  GPU grass-clipping particle system (kinematic physics on GPU)
  4.  GPU rain particle system (15,000 drops, no CPU position updates)
  5.  Waving flag with per-frame analytical normals
  6.  Sprinkler with Bezier water arc (glMap1d / glEvalMesh1)
  7.  Mouse object selection via colour picking
  8.  Help overlay (h key)
  9.  Fog improvements: EXP / EXP2 / LINEAR cycling, fog-matched clear colour
  10. Collision detection: circles + rotated boxes, sliding response


================================================================================
  COURSE CONCEPTS DEMONSTRATED
================================================================================

  Parametric surfaces          -- terrain (static) and flag (animated)
  Transformation of normals    -- analytical normals on terrain and flag
  GLSL vertex + fragment shdr  -- terrain, particles, rain, flag (4 programs)
  GPU particle systems         -- grass clippings and rain
  Parametric curves            -- Bezier sprinkler arc (glMap1d / glEvalMesh1)
  Display lists                -- fence geometry compiled once
  Polygon offset               -- gravel path, pick boxes
  Anti-aliased lines           -- Bezier arc, normal indicators
  Fog (EXP / EXP2 / LINEAR)    -- three modes, fog-matched sky colour
  Colour-based picking         -- mouse object selection
  Spotlight                    -- mower headlight (GL_LIGHT1, night only)
  Day/night lighting           -- time-of-day diffuse tint, ambient scale
  Texture mapping              -- 12 BMP textures, modulate mode
  Alpha blending               -- particles, Bezier arc, help overlay
  Two-sided lighting           -- flag back face
  First-person camera          -- walk mode with boundary clamps
  Multiple camera modes        -- 5 modes including follow and seat


================================================================================
  KEY BINDINGS  (full list -- also available in-program with h)
================================================================================

  1-5         View modes: Ortho / Persp / Walk / Follow Mower / Mower Seat
  m           Cycle view modes
  WASD        Drive mower (modes 4-5) or walk (mode 3)
  arrows      Look around (mode 3) or orbit camera (modes 1-2)
  PgUp/PgDn   Zoom (overhead modes)
  space       Pause / resume sun
  , / .       Sweep sun azimuth manually
  [ / ]       Lower / raise sun elevation
  l           Toggle lighting
  t           Toggle textures
  f           Toggle fog
  ;           Cycle fog mode: EXP -> EXP2 -> LINEAR
  g           Toggle GLSL per-pixel terrain shader
  p           Toggle GPU grass-clipping particles
  r           Cycle terrain mode: Dry -> Moderate -> Wet
  y           Toggle rain (auto-enabled in Wet mode)
  k           Toggle sprinkler on / off
  i           Enter / exit Inspector mode
  n / N       Cycle Inspector objects (forward / backward)
  v           Toggle surface normal indicators (Inspector only)
  h           Toggle help overlay
  b           Toggle axes
  + / -       Increase / decrease field of view
  0           Reset everything to defaults
  ESC / q     Quit


